<div id="review_2548520328" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2548520328" />
    <a title="Dorothy Himberc" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76362312-dorothy-himberc"><img alt="Dorothy Himberc" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1519937873p2/76362312.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2548520328?book_show_action=true">Oct 04, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dorothy Himberc" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dorothy Himberc" href="/user/show/76362312-dorothy-himberc">Dorothy Himberc</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2548520328" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer836218444799837994">A light work that lifted my spirits when I read it.<br/><br/>It is a play written by Marivaux in the epoch roughly of Watteau and Boucher - pretty, talkative people debating and falling in love and plotting small plots that are resolved by the end of the play - that centres around a headstrong young noblewoman, Silvia, who refuses an arranged marriage until she has had the chance to see her betrothed from a different perspective - from a servant&apos;s perspective. Her fear of being trapped in a loveless or ab</span>
  <span id="freeText836218444799837994" style="display:none">A light work that lifted my spirits when I read it.<br /><br />It is a play written by Marivaux in the epoch roughly of Watteau and Boucher - pretty, talkative people debating and falling in love and plotting small plots that are resolved by the end of the play - that centres around a headstrong young noblewoman, Silvia, who refuses an arranged marriage until she has had the chance to see her betrothed from a different perspective - from a servant's perspective. Her fear of being trapped in a loveless or abusive marriage is modern and not unreasonable. So she switches places with her maid Lisette, to the amusement of her meddling father Orgon and her teasing brother Mario. Then, to her shock, she believes that she is falling in love with the valet instead of the master.<br /><br />Larousse's notes talk about Le jeu's superficiality without finding that it's detrimental to the play. Marivaux, they explain, spends more time on wordplay between his characters than on digging deeply into the social issues attendant on the gap between rich and poor, servant and master, in 18th century France. These kinds of things he comments on in greater depth in other plays he wrote. The dialogue is entertaining even when it's predictable, for example when the characters jokingly claim in the clichéd polite phrase that they are so-and-so's servant. There are also moving moments, for example (although I may be too susceptible to attempts to tug the heartstrings) the idea of the hero kneeling desperately to the heroine, asking her to convince him of her indifference, so that he can finally stop being torn between love for her and the tyranny of the social hierarchy. And profundity isn't always necessary.<br /><br />If one thing jars on me in Le jeu de l'amour et du hasard, it is Silvia's role as the heroine. Her unworldly, spoiled, and stubborn actions and words are quite realistic and even endearing. But when she torments the hero I think she doesn't show any truthfulness or courage; and the hero's notion of love is far more romantic, brave and reflected. In Marivaux's time, I'm guessing, honesty and straightforwardness were thought of as masculine virtues, or servants' virtues (Lisette is certainly plainspoken enough) - not as virtues for heroines. Nowadays I guess that one expects different behaviour. But perhaps the idea is that Silvia can be cruel but that the audience is supposed to like her anyway.<br /><br />Aside from the name Silvia, other aspects of the play remind me of Shakespeare's comedies, like As You Like It. I think some of the traditions of the theatre in Marivaux's time, including the Harlequin figure of the Commedia dell'arte, peek out through the lines too, and lend an extra versatility to the text. Perfectly conceived and internally consistent though the play is, I suppose that there is less pressure on the audience to be sucked into a seamless world of feeling that never breaks the fourth wall and shouldn't be examined through the lens of common sense, than there is for a tragedy like Othello.</span>
  <a data-text-id="836218444799837994" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

